807. Pistores...qui...Eorum (v. 809). For the construction, repeated in VV. 813-6, 818-21, see note on V. 1, and cf. v. 110. Pistores, ‘millers.' There were no bakers (as distinguished from millers) at Rome till 173 nc. (Plin. N. H. xvm. xi. 28) (cf. ad V. 160). Scrofipasci, ἅπ. εῖρ. Furfuribus. The MSS. have furfure. Since the Abl. Sg. in -ἑ had often a by-form in -ῖ, editors formerly printed j'mfm·i. This reading however violates the law that an iambic word at the end of a line shall not be preceded by an iambic word—ending (Introd. iii. ξ 17). This might be remedied by transposing furfure qui alunt sues. But an examination of the passages in Latin writers where the word occurs proves that furfur Sing. was used in the sense of the husk of a single grain (Gell. XI. vii. 5, Plin. N. H. xviii. 304, xxii. 145), whereas the word for ‘chaffi bran' (the

word required here) is furfures Plur. (Varr. R. R. 11. v. 17, vi. 4, Colum. vm. iv. 1, ΧΠ. xliii. 3, Plin. N. H. xviii. 74, xxii. 120, xxviii. 188, Phaedr. IV. xviii. 3; cf. Marc. Empir. v, fin.). We may then confidently suppose that furfuribus was what Plautus wrote, especially since furfures occurs in v. 810. Probably in the ancient archetype of our MSS. the word was written FVRFVRIB. with the common contractiori of final -bus, and became at some time or other corrupted to s arfuw (through furfurz' 2).
